		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Black Mountain College</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:302px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Black_Mtn_College.jpg" class="image" title="The main building of the former Black Mountain College, on the grounds of Camp Rockmont, a summer camp for boys."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Black_Mtn_College.jpg/300px-Black_Mtn_College.jpg" width="300" height="225" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Black_Mtn_College.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
The main building of the former Black Mountain College, on the grounds of Camp Rockmont, a summer camp for boys.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Black Mountain College</b>, a university founded in 1933 near <a href="/wiki/Asheville,_North_Carolina" title="Asheville, North Carolina">Asheville, North Carolina</a> was a new kind of college in the United States in which the study of art was seen to be central to a liberal arts education, and in which <a href="/wiki/John_Dewey" title="John Dewey">John Dewey</a>'s principles of education played a major role. The school attracted students and faculty many of whom were or went on to become influential. Although notable even during its short life, the school closed after only twenty-four years in 1957. <sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
